    "result": {"data":{"challengeNode":{"challenge":{"videoId":null,"videoLocaleIds":null,"bilibiliIds":null,"title":"Task 49","description":"<section id=\"description\">\n<p><code>Can</code> is used to show that something is possible or someone is capable of doing something, while <code>can't</code> is a contraction of <code>cannot</code>, indicating that something is impossible or someone is incapable of doing something. Both words should be followed by the base form of verbs.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<p><code>I can swim.</code> (showing ability)</p>\n<p><code>I can't swim.</code> (showing inability or lack of ability)</p>\n</section>","challengeType":19,"helpCategory":"English","superBlock":"a2-english-for-developers","block":"learn-how-to-use-code-related-concepts-and-terms","fields":{"slug":"/learn/a2-english-for-developers/learn-how-to-use-code-related-concepts-and-terms/task-49","blockName":"learn-how-to-use-code-related-concepts-and-terms","tests":[]},"question":{"text":"<p>Which sentence is using <code>can</code> or <code>can't</code> correctly?</p>","answers":[{"answer":"<p><code>I can to play the guitar.</code></p>","feedback":"<p>This sentence is incorrect because <code>to</code> should not be used with <code>can</code>. The correct sentence would be: <code>I can play the guitar.</code></p>"},{"answer":"<p><code>She can't see without her glasses.</code></p>","feedback":null},{"answer":"<p><code>We can goes to the park tomorrow.</code></p>","feedback":"<p>The modal <code>can</code> is followed by a base form of the verb, so <code>goes</code> should be <code>go</code>.</p>"},{"answer":"<p><code>He can driving at night.</code></p>","feedback":"<p><code>Can</code> should be followed by the base form of the verb without <code>ing</code>. The correct sentence should be: <code>He can drive at night.</code></p>"}],"solution":2},"scene":null,"translationPending":false,"assignments":[],"audioPath":null}}},"pageContext":{"challengeMeta":{"blockHashSlug":"/learn/a2-en